"**CORE_NARRATIVE:** \nTraditional light field depth estimation remains fundamentally crippled by the EPI paradigm's reliance on rigid 2D slicing and a fragile global Lambertian assumption, which discards over 65% of angular data and creates an unbreakable accuracy ceiling in real-world, non-Lambertian scenes. To shatter this bottleneck, we completely abandon EPI architectures and propose MACVO-Net, a full-angular 4D cost volume framework that utilizes MRI-like frequency analysis and SAM-guided energy adjustments to explicitly model non-Lambertian physics. By transforming naturally flat cost volumes from a catastrophic failure mode into an explicit uncertainty signal, our approach successfully propagates accurate depth across highly specular and translucent materials where traditional methods structurally fail.\n\n**INTRO_HOOK:** \nOpen by highlighting the critical paradox in modern light field vision: while practical applications like autonomous navigation and AR are dominated by complex non-Lambertian materials (glass, metal), traditional EPI networks deliberately discard over 65% of the light field's angular information, causing them to fail with severe texture-copying artifacts exactly where robust depth perception is most needed.\n\n**GAP_BRIDGE:** \nTransition from related work by proving that no amount of EPI network refinement can overcome the MAE lower bound of 0.28, because the root cause is structural—evaluating only 34.6% of views along rigid 2D directions strips away the physical multi-view evidence required to decode specular reflections. This establishes a hard dead-end for EPI methods, necessitating a ground-up redesign of light field processing that abandons 2D slope extraction in favor of a holistic, physics-driven 4D cost volume.\n\n**METHOD_JUSTIFY:** \nThe design of MACVO-Net directly mirrors the physics of non-Lambertian light transport: an MRI-inspired angular frequency analysis (via dual-mask modeling) is introduced to physically classify materials in the frequency domain, which then drives a SAM-guided adaptive energy adjustment mechanism to suppress Lambertian \"smooth artifacts\" (down to 15%) and amplify true non-Lambertian signals (up to 150%). This high-SNR feature space allows the network to safely replace EPI slopes with an explicit 4D cost volume across all 81 views, mathematically utilizing the naturally flat cost volumes of specular regions as a geometric certainty map to guide U-Net multi-scale neighborhood propagation.\n\n**EXPERIMENT_VALIDATE:** \nStructure the results section to explicitly quantify the shattering of the previous EPI performance ceiling, highlighting drastic metric improvements (such as the 495.8% ratio leap on the Apple dataset) to prove the superiority of the 4D cost volume in high-frequency specular regions. Use visual ablation studies to demonstrate that the GCD and SAM-guided energy adjustments effectively eliminate the \"texture-copying\" artifacts prevalent in baseline models, physically validating the accuracy of the uncertainty propagation in complex translucent and scattering scenes.\n\n**CONCLUSION_ECHO:** \nClose by reiterating that the EPI paradigm's 2D structural limitations are a fatal flaw for real-world depth estimation, and summarize how MACVO-Net’s full-view physically-grounded architecture has fundamentally solved this by turning non-Lambertian uncertainty from a system weakness into a mathematically modeled strength. Ultimately, frame this work as the necessary catalyst for transitioning light field depth estimation out of rigid laboratory assumptions and into the complex, specular reality of modern robotic and industrial applications."